<p>
  A <strong>Transient Component</strong> is a custom element that replaces itself with a semantically correct native HTML element during initialization.
  The transient element exists only long enough to determine <em>what</em> to render — then it disappears, leaving no wrapper node in the DOM.
  See the <a href="/semantics/">Semantics</a> page for terminology.
</p>

<h3>Why Transient?</h3>

<p>
  Frameworks solve the "dynamic element tag" problem at compile time (JSX, templates) or via virtual DOM.
  Web components don't have this luxury — a custom element is always present in the DOM tree.
  A transient component bridges this gap: it's a custom element that <strong>self-destructs</strong> after choosing the right native element.
</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Framework Solution</th><th>Web Everything Solution</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Heading level depends on nesting</td>
    <td>React: HeadingLevelContext + useContext</td>
    <td>AutoHeading: resolves level from InjectorRoot, replaces itself with &lt;hN&gt;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Link vs button depends on href</td>
    <td>Vue: &lt;component :is="tag"&gt;</td>
    <td>SmartLink: replaces with &lt;a&gt; or &lt;button&gt; based on attributes</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Wrapper-free structural containers</td>
    <td>Angular: &lt;ng-container&gt; (no DOM output)</td>
    <td>Comment markers (virtual elements) for structural directives</td>
  </tr>
</table>

