<h3>Self-Replacement Lifecycle</h3>

<p>The replacement follows a safe, deterministic sequence:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>connectedCallback fires</strong> — the custom element is in the DOM, attributes and children are accessible</li>
  <li><strong>Determine replacement</strong> — read attributes, query injector chain, compute the target element tag</li>
  <li><strong>Create replacement element</strong> — <code>document.createElement(tag)</code></li>
  <li><strong>Transfer attributes</strong> — copy all attributes (except internal ones) to the new element</li>
  <li><strong>Transfer children</strong> — <code>replacement.append(...this.childNodes)</code> (move, not clone — preserves listeners on children)</li>
  <li><strong>Schedule replacement</strong> — <code>queueMicrotask(() => this.replaceWith(replacement))</code></li>
  <li><strong>Microtask runs</strong> — the transient element is removed, the native element takes its place. Zero visual flash.</li>
</ol>

<pre><code>// Simplified TransientElement base class
class TransientElement extends HTMLElement {
  connectedCallback() {
    const tag = this.resolveTag();         // subclass decides
    const el = document.createElement(tag);

    // Transfer attributes
    for (const { name, value } of this.attributes) {
      if (!name.startsWith('data-transient-')) {
        el.setAttribute(name, value);
      }
    }

    // Transfer children (move, not clone)
    el.append(...this.childNodes);

    // Safe deferred replacement
    queueMicrotask(() => this.replaceWith(el));
  }

  /** Subclasses override to determine the replacement tag */
  resolveTag(): string {
    throw new Error('resolveTag() must be implemented');
  }
}</code></pre>

<h3>Use Case 1: Accessible Auto-Heading</h3>

<p>
  The <strong>&lt;auto-heading&gt;</strong> element replaces itself with the correct <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>–<code>&lt;h6&gt;</code> based on document nesting.
  This solves the reusable component problem: a card, sidebar, or article section can use <code>&lt;auto-heading&gt;</code> without hardcoding a heading level.
</p>

<h4>Level Resolution (priority order)</h4>

<table>
  <tr><th>Source</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Example</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>1. Explicit attribute</td>
    <td><code>level="3"</code> on the element</td>
    <td><code>&lt;auto-heading level="3"&gt;Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;</code></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>2. Injector provider</td>
    <td>InjectorRoot resolves <code>'headingLevel'</code> from ancestor chain</td>
    <td>A &lt;section&gt; wrapper provides level 2; nested sections increment</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>3. DOM traversal (fallback)</td>
    <td>Count &lt;section&gt;, &lt;article&gt;, &lt;nav&gt;, &lt;aside&gt; ancestors</td>
    <td>3 sectioning ancestors → <code>&lt;h4&gt;</code></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h4>Injector-Based Level (Recommended)</h4>

<pre><code>// Section component increments heading level in its injector scope
class SectionElement extends HTMLElement {
  connectedCallback() {
    const parentLevel = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(this, 'headingLevel') ?? 0;
    const injector = InjectorRoot.ensureInjector(this);
    injector.set('headingLevel', parentLevel + 1);
  }
}

// AutoHeading reads from injector chain
class AutoHeading extends TransientElement {
  resolveTag() {
    // 1. Explicit attribute
    const explicit = this.getAttribute('level');
    if (explicit) return `h${Math.min(Number(explicit), 6)}`;

    // 2. Injector provider
    const injected = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(this, 'headingLevel');
    if (injected) return `h${Math.min(injected, 6)}`;

    // 3. DOM traversal fallback
    return `h${Math.min(this.#countSectioningAncestors() + 1, 6)}`;
  }

  #countSectioningAncestors(): number {
    let count = 0;
    let el = this.parentElement;
    while (el) {
      if (el.matches('section, article, nav, aside')) count++;
      el = el.parentElement;
    }
    return count;
  }
}</code></pre>

<h4>Usage</h4>

<pre><code>&lt;!-- Author writes: --&gt;
&lt;section&gt;
  &lt;auto-heading&gt;Page Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;        &lt;!-- becomes &lt;h1&gt; --&gt;
  &lt;section&gt;
    &lt;auto-heading&gt;Section Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;    &lt;!-- becomes &lt;h2&gt; --&gt;
    &lt;section&gt;
      &lt;auto-heading&gt;Sub-section&lt;/auto-heading&gt;    &lt;!-- becomes &lt;h3&gt; --&gt;
    &lt;/section&gt;
  &lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Use Case 2: Smart Link</h3>

<p>
  A <strong>&lt;smart-link&gt;</strong> replaces itself with <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> (when <code>href</code> is present) or <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> (when no href).
  This avoids the ARIA anti-pattern of <code>&lt;div role="link"&gt;</code> and ensures correct semantics for both navigation and actions.
</p>

<pre><code>&lt;!-- Navigation → becomes &lt;a href="/about"&gt; --&gt;
&lt;smart-link href="/about"&gt;About&lt;/smart-link&gt;

&lt;!-- Action → becomes &lt;button type="button"&gt; --&gt;
&lt;smart-link&gt;Delete Item&lt;/smart-link&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Use Case 3: Ergonomic Directive Syntax</h3>

<p>
  Custom elements like <code>&lt;for-each&gt;</code> provide friendlier authoring syntax than comment markers.
  The element replaces itself with start/end comment markers, then the structural directive manages the comment-bounded region.
</p>

<pre><code>&lt;!-- Author writes: --&gt;
&lt;for-each store="items" as="item"&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;{{ item.name }}&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/for-each&gt;

&lt;!-- After connectedCallback, DOM becomes: --&gt;
&lt;!-- for-each:start store="items" as="item" --&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Alpha&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Beta&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;!-- for-each:end --&gt;</code></pre>

<p>
  This combines <strong>author ergonomics</strong> (custom element syntax) with the <strong>proven comment-based implementation</strong> that preserves CSS Grid/Flex parent-child relationships.
</p>

