<h3>SSR Considerations</h3>

<p>
  Transient components are <strong>client-side progressive enhancement</strong>.
  Custom elements require JavaScript to run <code>connectedCallback</code> — crawlers and screen readers see the pre-upgrade HTML.
</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Approach</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Server-computed</td>
    <td>SSR layer (e.g., Eleventy shortcode) computes the correct native element at build time. Client-side transient element is not needed.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Annotated fallback</td>
    <td>Server emits <code>&lt;auto-heading data-level="2"&gt;Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;</code>. Client upgrades to <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>. Pre-JS HTML has the annotation for styling.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Progressive enhancement</td>
    <td>Server emits a generic element (<code>&lt;div role="heading" aria-level="2"&gt;</code>). Client replaces with native <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>Pitfalls &amp; Constraints</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Event listeners on the transient element are lost.</strong> Use listeners on children or the replacement. This is by design — transient elements are replaced before user interaction.</li>
  <li><strong>CSS rules targeting the custom element tag</strong> (e.g., <code>auto-heading { color: red }</code>) will not match the replacement. Style the replacement tag instead.</li>
  <li><strong>HTML parser restrictions:</strong> A custom element inside <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;select&gt;</code>, or other restricted-content elements will be moved by parser error recovery. Transient elements should not be placed in parser-restricted contexts.</li>
  <li><strong>MutationObserver</strong> sees the replacement as a <code>childList</code> mutation: <code>removedNodes</code> contains the original, <code>addedNodes</code> contains the replacement. This is clean and expected.</li>
</ul>

<h3>API Draft</h3>

<pre><code>/** Base class for transient custom elements */
abstract class TransientElement extends HTMLElement {
  /** Determine the replacement element tag name */
  abstract resolveTag(): string;

  /** Optional: configure which attributes to exclude from transfer */
  get excludedAttributes(): string[] {
    return [];
  }
}

/** Accessible heading that resolves level from context */
class AutoHeading extends TransientElement {
  resolveTag(): string; // returns 'h1'–'h6'
}

/** Mixin for adding self-replacement to any custom element */
function withSelfReplacement&lt;T extends CustomElementConstructor&gt;(
  Base: T,
  resolveTag: (el: InstanceType&lt;T&gt;) => string
): T;

/** Utility: calculate heading level from DOM nesting */
function calculateHeadingLevel(element: Element): number;</code></pre>

